  "prompt": "Why are liquids not allowed on flights?",
  "response": "Liquids are restricted on flights primarily due to security concerns related to potential terrorist threats. In 2006, a plot was uncovered to detonate liquid explosives on transatlantic flights, which led to stricter regulations. The current rules, known as the 3-1-1 rule in the United States, limit passengers to:\n\n1. Liquids in containers no larger than 3.4 ounces (100 milliliters)\n2. Containers must be placed in a single, clear, quart-sized plastic bag\n3. One bag per passenger\n\nThese restrictions help prevent the possibility of bringing large quantities of potentially dangerous liquids onto an aircraft. Exceptions are made for medically necessary liquids, baby formula, and some other special circumstances, which are typically screened separately.\n\nThe goal is to minimize the risk of liquid-based explosives or other harmful substances being brought onto planes, thus enhancing overall flight safety.",
